<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO DR. SPATZ</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov 17 21:20:36 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Dr. Spatz,<br>
I have been enlightened and thanks for your honest and complete response. It seems if I am not mistaken that you were already along your way (intern or resident?) to becoming a doctor when the escalation started.  Most of our doctors were in their residency when they shipped over.  I had two during my tour.  Both were neurosurgeons, both were good and fair men. We went on a first name basis except when we had &quot;company&quot; from headquarters or other officiers. (they were both captains) Then proper military courtesys were extended.<br><br>
As far as Saddam Hussien is concerned, I hope we can solve some of the school boy polotics thru diplomacy. A friend of mine lost a nephew in Desert Storm. He was a Navy A6 driver. I just hate to see any of our country&quot;s best destroyed when a good ol' nipple twist would straightend things out. I'm not what you would refer to as a religious man (however I never saw a atheist in a firefight or a foxhole either) but I pray we don't go to war over this.  I agree, we do grow wiser with age.  Along with being more patient, observant and the ability to speak less and listen more.  As for the fatboy thing, it's a physical theorm that age is directly proportional to weight gain.<p>I also hope that not only you and but everyone that has been involved in this dialogue can continue. I just found this site and have read all the posts front and back. I wanted to respond to you earlier but I will never write a letter to someone in anger, unless it's to myself. I have found over the years that by doing this it will not be something you will regret later, espically in business and personal relationships.  Good decisions are made through experience, and experience is made through bad decisions.<br><br>
Yes Barry me boyo' the neck hairs were standing straight up and the nostrils flared when I read your first post. But as I said earlier, you and everybody else in this country is entitled to the freedom of speech. It's my gift as a veteran to you. But you can be, shall we say, be &quot;abrasive&quot; and nobody likes sand in between their cheeks. It makes them irritable. We don't need to use a M16 when a rubber band will do when talking to each other. Examine what is said, not him who says it.<br><br>
To my fellow veterans. Remember when we woukd pass each other on a road? Even though we didn't know each other what was the universal greeting? Let's all continue the dialogue. We've been through worse.<br><br>
Bacsi
